---

<BaseLayout
  title="Fundamentals 4 — Jesus Garcia"
  description="Unfolding case study: Colostomy Care and Teaching — FUN-04"
>

  <div class="breadcrumb">
    <a href={base}>Home</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <a href={`${base}cases/`}>Cases</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <a href={`${base}cases/fundamentals/`}>Fundamentals</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <span>Fundamentals 4 — Jesus Garcia</span>
  </div>

  <!-- ── CASE HEADER ───────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <div class="case-header">
    <span class="card-tag">GI / Ostomy</span>
    <h1>Fundamentals 4 — Jesus Garcia</h1>
    <p class="case-subtitle">Colostomy Care and Teaching</p>
    <div class="case-meta">
      <span>👤 Jesus Garcia, 28 years, Hispanic Male</span>
      <span>⏱ Scenario: 20 – 25 minutes</span>
      <span>💬 Debrief: 20 – 25 minutes</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ── HOW TO USE ────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <div class="callout callout-info">
    <strong>📖 How to Use This Unfolding Case Study</strong>
    <p>Work through each phase in order. Information is revealed progressively — exactly as it would be in a real clinical encounter. Before reading each answer, pause and reason through the question yourself. Use the <strong>▶ Reveal Answer</strong> toggles to check your thinking.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       PHASE 1 — YOU ARRIVE AT THE BEDSIDE
  ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase1">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 1</span>
      <h2>You Arrive at the Bedside</h2>
    </div>

    <p class="phase-intro">
      You are the evening nurse on a medical-surgical unit. You receive handoff report and head to see Jesus Garcia for the first time.
    </p>

    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📋 Handoff Report</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Patient</th><td>Jesus Garcia</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Age / Sex</th><td>28 years · Male</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Race / Ethnicity</th><td>Hispanic</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Admission Dx</th><td>Dehydration</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Secondary Dx</th><td>Ulcerative colitis; s/p partial colectomy with transverse colostomy (15 days ago)</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Allergy</th><td>NKDA</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Code Status</th><td>Full code</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Admission</th><td>Tuesday evening</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Support</th><td>Girlfriend Virginia at bedside</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>💊 Current Medications (MAR)</h3>
        <ul class="med-list">
          <li>Mesalamine (Asacol) 800 mg PO</li>
          <li>Ondansetron (Zofran) 4 mg IVP PRN nausea</li>
          <li>0.9% Normal Saline IV at 125 mL/hr</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>🚪 Entering the Room — What You Observe</h3>
      <p>
        Jesus is lying in bed, turned away from the door. The room is quiet and dim. He barely acknowledges your entry. His girlfriend Virginia is at the bedside and greets you warmly. As you approach, you notice the colostomy pouch is visible from the side — it appears full and is leaking at the seal.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h3>🔒 SWIPE Safety Assessment</h3>
    <p>Before touching the patient, perform your environmental safety check:</p>
    <table class="data-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Letter</th><th>Check</th><th>What You Find</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>S</strong></td><td>Siderails up</td><td>Both rails up — <span class="text-success">OK</span></td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>W</strong></td><td>Wristband on, matches chart</td><td>Present and correct</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>I</strong></td><td>IV lines — site, patency, rate, label</td><td>Right forearm, no redness; 0.9% NS infusing at ordered rate (125 mL/hr)</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>P</strong></td><td>Pull cord / call light within reach</td><td>Call light within reach — <span class="text-success">OK</span></td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>E</strong></td><td>Equipment — bed position, socks, path clear</td><td>Bed in low position; path clear</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: What do you observe about Jesus's demeanor and what does the colostomy pouch tell you?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Jesus's demeanor — psychosocial concerns:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Withdrawn, turned away from the door, minimal eye contact — early signs of psychosocial distress and body image concerns</li>
          <li>Barely acknowledging your presence suggests avoidance behavior — emotionally significant</li>
          <li>Virginia greeting you warmly while Jesus is withdrawn may indicate he is relying on her as a buffer</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Colostomy pouch assessment:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Pouch appearing full and leaking at the seal = needs immediate emptying AND appliance assessment/change</li>
          <li>Leaking pouch puts peristomal skin at risk for excoriation and breakdown — a nursing safety priority</li>
          <li>Virginia doing all colostomy care = knowledge deficit and care dependence — critical patient education need</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Priority approach:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Establish therapeutic relationship FIRST — do not rush to procedures without acknowledgment</li>
          <li>Introduce yourself, verify two identifiers, and explain what you are going to do before doing it</li>
          <li>Address the leaking pouch clinically, but be mindful of privacy and emotional sensitivity</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <!-- connector -->
  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ As you complete your introduction and initial safety check, you proceed to a full assessment…</div>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       PHASE 2 — ASSESSMENT FINDINGS
  ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase2">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 2</span>
      <h2>Assessment Findings</h2>
    </div>

    <p class="phase-intro">
      You perform a systematic assessment. Jesus cooperates minimally, answering in brief sentences. Virginia provides additional history when prompted.
    </p>

    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🌡️ Vital Signs</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Temperature</th><td>37.2°C (99.0°F) — normal</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Heart Rate</th><td>108 bpm — <span class="badge-warning">TACHYCARDIA</span> (dehydration indicator)</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Blood Pressure</th><td>104/68 mmHg — <span class="badge-warning">LOW</span> (dehydration)</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Respiratory Rate</th><td>18/min — normal</td></tr>
            <tr><th>SpO₂</th><td>98% on room air — normal</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Pain</th><td>3/10 abdominal cramping</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>💧 Hydration Assessment</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Mucous membranes: <strong>dry and tacky</strong></li>
          <li>Skin turgor: <strong>decreased</strong> — tenting &gt;2 seconds</li>
          <li>Capillary refill: <strong>3 seconds (delayed)</strong></li>
          <li>Urine output: <strong>15 mL/hr</strong> <span class="badge-danger">CRITICALLY LOW</span> (goal ≥ 30 mL/hr)</li>
          <li>Urine color: dark amber/concentrated</li>
          <li>Reports decreased oral intake since discharge — "I don't feel like eating"</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🩹 Stoma Assessment</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Stoma color</th><td>Pink-red, moist — <span class="text-success">NORMAL</span></td></tr>
            <tr><th>Peristomal skin</th><td><span class="badge-warning">Mild redness/irritation</span> from leakage</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Pouch seal</th><td><span class="badge-danger">LEAKING</span> — requires immediate change</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Output character</th><td>Watery/liquid, moderate amount (brown-green liquid)</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Stoma size</th><td>Approximately 2 cm diameter</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Location</th><td>Transverse colostomy — upper abdomen</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📊 Expected Lab Findings</h3>
        <p><em>Labs ordered — anticipate these results based on clinical presentation:</em></p>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>BUN</th><td>Elevated (↑ with dehydration)</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Creatinine</th><td>Elevated (↑ with dehydration)</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Urine specific gravity</th><td>Elevated &gt; 1.030 (concentrated)</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Sodium</th><td>Possibly elevated (hypernatremia from free water loss)</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Hematocrit</th><td>Possibly elevated (hemoconcentration)</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: What do these findings tell you about Jesus's fluid status and what interventions are priority?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Dehydration confirmed — multiple indicators:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>HR 108 + BP 104/68 = compensatory tachycardia with early hypotension</li>
          <li>Dry mucous membranes + skin tenting = interstitial fluid deficit</li>
          <li>Urine output 15 mL/hr = kidneys compensating; critically below target of 30 mL/hr</li>
          <li>Dark amber urine = high concentration, poor renal perfusion</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Why is the transverse colostomy relevant to dehydration?</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Transverse colostomy bypasses a significant portion of the large intestine where water reabsorption normally occurs</li>
          <li>Output is watery/liquid — ongoing free fluid losses daily</li>
          <li>These patients need significantly higher oral fluid intake than the average person</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Priority interventions — in order:</strong></p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Priority 1:</strong> Verify IV fluid (0.9% NS) running at 125 mL/hr as ordered — assess IV site</li>
          <li><strong>Priority 2:</strong> Address leaking colostomy pouch — skin breakdown risk (urgent but not emergent)</li>
          <li><strong>Priority 3:</strong> Notify provider of urine output 15 mL/hr if not already known</li>
          <li><strong>Priority 4:</strong> Measure and document hourly urine output</li>
          <li><strong>Priority 5:</strong> Monitor electrolytes per orders</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <!-- connector -->
  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ You prepare to change the colostomy appliance — but first, something important happens…</div>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       PHASE 3 — BODY IMAGE AND THERAPEUTIC COMMUNICATION
  ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase3">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 3</span>
      <h2>Body Image &amp; Therapeutic Communication</h2>
    </div>

    <p class="phase-intro">
      While you prepare to change the colostomy appliance, Jesus makes a quiet but important statement that changes your approach.
    </p>

    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>💬 What Jesus Says</h3>
      <p>
        Jesus says quietly, still turned away: <em>"I don't want to look at it. Virginia does everything for me. Can't you just… do it without me watching?"</em>
      </p>
      <p style="margin-top: 0.75rem;">
        Virginia adds: <em>"He won't even look at it. He says he doesn't feel like himself anymore. He's been really down since the surgery."</em>
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>✅ Therapeutic Communication — What TO Say</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><em>"It sounds like this has been really hard to adjust to. That makes complete sense."</em></li>
          <li><em>"Many people feel exactly the way you do when they first have an ostomy."</em></li>
          <li><em>"What worries you most about it?"</em></li>
          <li><em>"You don't have to do anything today that you're not ready for — let's just talk."</em></li>
          <li><em>"Would it be okay if I tell you a little about what I'm doing as I go?"</em></li>
          <li><em>"You've been through a significant surgery. It's okay to feel like things have changed."</em></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🚫 What NOT to Say</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><span class="text-danger">✗</span> <em>"You have to learn this before you leave."</em></li>
          <li><span class="text-danger">✗</span> <em>"It's really not that bad."</em></li>
          <li><span class="text-danger">✗</span> <em>"Your girlfriend can't keep doing this forever."</em></li>
          <li><span class="text-danger">✗</span> <em>"You should be grateful it helped your colitis."</em></li>
          <li><span class="text-danger">✗</span> <em>"Most people get used to it."</em></li>
          <li><span class="text-danger">✗</span> <em>"You're young — this shouldn't bother you."</em></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3>🧠 Body Image Concerns — Jesus's Perspective (Age 28)</h3>
    <table class="data-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Concern</th><th>Clinical Significance</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Sexuality and intimacy concerns at age 28</td><td>Young adult identity closely tied to body image; fear of how Virginia perceives him</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Loss of control over bodily function</td><td>Autonomy and independence are central developmental needs of young adulthood</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Fear of odor and leakage in social situations</td><td>Social isolation and withdrawal — risk for depression</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Uncertainty about returning to normal activities</td><td>Work, recreation, and social engagement may feel impossible</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Altered self-concept</td><td>"He says he doesn't feel like himself" = disturbed body image (nursing diagnosis)</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: How do you therapeutically address Jesus's body image concerns without dismissing his feelings or overwhelming him?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Step 1 — Validate first, always:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><em>"It makes complete sense to feel this way. This is a significant change — it's only been 15 days."</em></li>
          <li>Validation does NOT mean agreement — it means acknowledgment. This is the foundation of therapeutic communication.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Step 2 — Normalize the experience with facts:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>United Ostomy Associations of America (UOAA): over 700,000 Americans live with ostomies — and live full, active lives</li>
          <li>Many young adults return to sports, travel, and intimate relationships after ostomy surgery</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Step 3 — Use motivational interviewing:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><em>"What would help you feel more in control right now?"</em></li>
          <li>Meet him where he is — do not push participation before he is ready</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Step 4 — Address sexuality openly and professionally:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><em>"A colostomy does not have to change intimacy. Many people find that with time and the right support, this becomes just one part of who they are."</em></li>
          <li>Mention discreet, flat, odor-resistant modern pouching systems — this directly addresses practical fears</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Step 5 — Involve Virginia with permission:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Virginia is a support resource, but Jesus must eventually be independent — assess his readiness</li>
          <li>Ask: <em>"Is it okay if Virginia stays while I do this?"</em> — respect autonomy</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Step 6 — Refer to specialized resources:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>WOC (Wound, Ostomy, Continence) Nurse consult — specialized psychosocial AND technical support</li>
          <li>UOAA peer support — connection with others who have ostomies and live well</li>
          <li>Mental health/counseling referral if body image disturbance persists</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <!-- connector -->
  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ Jesus agrees to watch. You proceed with the colostomy appliance change…</div>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       PHASE 4 — COLOSTOMY APPLIANCE CHANGE
  ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase4">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 4</span>
      <h2>Colostomy Appliance Change</h2>
    </div>

    <p class="phase-intro">
      Jesus has agreed to watch while you change the appliance. Virginia asks if she can stay and you check with Jesus — he nods. You explain each step clearly as you go, using this as an informal teaching opportunity.
    </p>

    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🛒 Supplies Needed</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>New one-piece or two-piece pouching system</li>
          <li>Skin barrier/wafer (pre-cut or cut-to-fit)</li>
          <li>Scissors and stoma measuring guide</li>
          <li>Warm water and soft clean washcloth (or ostomy wipes)</li>
          <li>Ostomy paste (if gaps or irregularities present)</li>
          <li>New drain clamp for bottom of drainable pouch</li>
          <li>Gloves (non-sterile)</li>
          <li>Disposal bag (sealed, odor-barrier)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>⚠️ Quick Stoma Color Reference</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Color / Appearance</th><th>Meaning / Action</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Pink-red, moist</td><td><span class="text-success">Normal — healthy perfusion</span></td></tr>
            <tr><td>Pale or white</td><td><span class="badge-warning">Poor circulation — notify provider</span></td></tr>
            <tr><td>Dark red or purple</td><td><span class="badge-danger">Venous ischemia — NOTIFY PROVIDER</span></td></tr>
            <tr><td>Black or gray</td><td><span class="badge-danger">Necrosis — EMERGENCY</span></td></tr>
            <tr><td>Dry or dull surface</td><td>Assess hydration status</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Small bleed with touch</td><td>Normal — stoma is highly vascular</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Bright red bleeding, unprovoked</td><td>Assess further; notify if persistent</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3>📋 Step-by-Step Procedure</h3>
    <table class="data-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Step</th><th>Action</th><th>Key Points / Rationale</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>1</td><td>Perform hand hygiene; don non-sterile gloves; ensure privacy (close curtain/door)</td><td>Infection control; respect dignity</td></tr>
        <tr><td>2</td><td>Gently remove old pouching system — push down on skin while lifting adhesive edge</td><td>Do NOT pull away from skin; skin tears easily. "Peel-push" technique</td></tr>
        <tr><td>3</td><td>Empty remaining output into toilet or basin before discarding old pouch</td><td>Reduces odor; prevents spill during removal</td></tr>
        <tr><td>4</td><td>Clean peristomal skin with warm water and soft washcloth; pat thoroughly DRY</td><td>No soap with additives; no alcohol wipes; skin must be completely dry for adhesive to seal</td></tr>
        <tr><td>5</td><td>Inspect peristomal skin: look for redness, excoriation, rash, breakdown, moisture damage</td><td>Document findings; notify WOC nurse if breakdown present</td></tr>
        <tr><td>6</td><td>Assess stoma: color, moisture, size, protrusion</td><td>Pink-red and moist = normal. Document any changes from baseline</td></tr>
        <tr><td>7</td><td>Measure stoma with measuring guide; cut barrier opening 1/8 inch LARGER than stoma diameter</td><td>Too small = stoma trauma; too large = skin exposed to output</td></tr>
        <tr><td>8</td><td>Apply ostomy paste to fill any gaps or skin irregularities if present</td><td>Improves seal; prevents leakage under wafer</td></tr>
        <tr><td>9</td><td>Center new wafer/barrier over stoma; press firmly from center outward; hold with warm palm for 30–60 seconds</td><td>Body heat activates adhesive; ensures complete seal</td></tr>
        <tr><td>10</td><td>Secure drain clamp on bottom of drainable pouch</td><td>Verify clamp is fully closed before releasing patient</td></tr>
        <tr><td>11</td><td>Remove gloves, perform hand hygiene; dispose of old appliance in sealed disposal bag</td><td>Odor control; infection control; proper waste disposal</td></tr>
        <tr><td>12</td><td>Document: stoma color/appearance, peristomal skin condition, output character/amount, patient response</td><td>Accurate documentation; legal requirement; supports continuity of care</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: After completing the appliance change, Jesus says he watched the whole thing. What is your next clinical priority?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>This is a significant milestone — acknowledge it therapeutically:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><em>"That took courage. You watched the whole thing — that is the first step, and it's a big one."</em></li>
          <li>Genuine positive reinforcement builds motivation and self-efficacy</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Assess readiness for participation:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Use teach-back: <em>"What did you notice about the color of your stoma?"</em></li>
          <li>If he can answer, his cognitive engagement is intact — build on this</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Plan gradual teaching progression:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Today: Watch the procedure — ✅ accomplished</li>
          <li>Next visit: Help hold supplies and pass items</li>
          <li>Following: Participate in one step (e.g., empty the pouch)</li>
          <li>Goal before discharge: Independent pouch emptying; then change</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Document and communicate progress:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Document: "Patient observed colostomy appliance change in its entirety. Tolerated without turning away. Expressed willingness to participate in next step."</li>
          <li>Notify WOC nurse: patient watched procedure today — coordinate next teaching session</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <!-- connector -->
  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ With the appliance secured and the acute skin issue addressed, you begin structured patient teaching…</div>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       PHASE 5 — PATIENT TEACHING
  ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase5">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 5</span>
      <h2>Patient Teaching</h2>
    </div>

    <p class="phase-intro">
      Patient teaching for colostomy care must be gradual, patient-centered, and verified using teach-back. Jesus has agreed to begin learning. Virginia is also present.
    </p>

    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📚 Teaching Priorities (in order)</h3>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>How to empty the pouch</strong> — FIRST skill; most frequent task (multiple times daily)</li>
          <li><strong>When to empty</strong> — when pouch is 1/3 to 1/2 full (prevents leaks, reduces weight)</li>
          <li><strong>Stoma assessment basics</strong> — what normal looks like vs. when to call</li>
          <li><strong>How to change the pouching system</strong> — most complex; build up to this</li>
          <li><strong>Dietary considerations</strong> — fluid intake, foods that affect output, odor management</li>
          <li><strong>When to call the provider</strong> — red flag recognition</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🗣️ Teach-Back Examples</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><em>"Can you show me how you would empty the pouch?"</em></li>
          <li><em>"Tell me in your own words — when would you need to empty the bag?"</em></li>
          <li><em>"What color should your stoma be? What color would make you call the nurse right away?"</em></li>
          <li><em>"What are two foods that might cause more gas with your ostomy?"</em></li>
          <li><em>"How much water should you be drinking each day?"</em></li>
          <li><em>"Name two signs that would make you call your doctor."</em></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3>🥗 Dietary Guidance — Colostomy</h3>
    <table class="data-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Category</th><th>Examples</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
