    <h3>💊 Mesalamine (Asacol / Delzicol) 800 mg PO</h3>
    <table class="data-table med-table">
      <tbody>
        <tr><th>Classification</th><td>Aminosalicylate / GI anti-inflammatory</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Indication</th><td>Treatment and maintenance of remission of ulcerative colitis</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Mechanism</th><td>Local anti-inflammatory effect on colonic mucosa; inhibits prostaglandin synthesis and reduces mucosal inflammation</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Adverse effects</th><td><strong>GI:</strong> diarrhea, flatulence, nausea, vomiting, abdominal cramping; <strong>GU:</strong> interstitial nephritis, renal failure (rare); pancreatitis (rare)</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Contraindications</th><td>Hypersensitivity to sulfonamides or salicylates — always verify allergy history before administration</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Nursing precautions</th><td>Assess for salicylate allergy prior to first dose; monitor renal function during therapy; do NOT crush, break, or chew enteric-coated tablets (destroys delayed-release mechanism)</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Patient teaching</th><td>Take with food if GI upset occurs; report decreased urination or swelling (renal symptoms); do not skip doses even when feeling well — maintenance therapy is essential; swallow whole</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">💉 Ondansetron (Zofran) 4 mg IVP PRN</h3>
    <table class="data-table med-table">
      <tbody>
        <tr><th>Classification</th><td>Antiemetic (5-HT3 serotonin receptor antagonist)</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Indication</th><td>Prevention and treatment of postoperative nausea and vomiting</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Route / Administration</th><td>IV push — administer undiluted over 2–5 minutes; do NOT push faster (increases risk of QT prolongation)</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Adverse effects</th><td>Headache, constipation, diarrhea; <strong>QT prolongation</strong> (particularly with high doses or pre-existing risk factors)</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Contraindications</th><td>Hypersensitivity; congenital long QT syndrome; caution with other QT-prolonging drugs</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Nursing precautions</th><td>Monitor cardiac rhythm if QT prolongation risk present; assess effectiveness within 30 minutes of dose; monitor for constipation — especially significant in colostomy patients as it may affect output</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Patient teaching</th><td>Report any irregular heartbeat or palpitations; medication should relieve nausea within 30 minutes; report if nausea is not improving</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">💧 IV Fluids — 0.9% Normal Saline / Lactated Ringer's 125 mL/hr</h3>
    <table class="data-table med-table">
      <tbody>
        <tr><th>Classification</th><td>Isotonic crystalloid solution</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Indication</th><td>Treatment of dehydration; replacement of fluid losses from colostomy output; restoration of intravascular volume</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Why isotonic?</th><td>Expands extracellular fluid (ECF) without shifting fluid into or out of cells; appropriate for true volume depletion from GI losses</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Nursing precautions</th><td>Monitor urine output hourly (goal ≥ 30 mL/hr — key indicator of adequate rehydration); daily weights; assess lung sounds for fluid overload; IV site assessment every 4 hours; monitor electrolytes</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Patient teaching</th><td>Explain purpose of IV fluid therapy; report any pain, swelling, or redness at IV site; report if breathing changes or feels difficult (fluid overload symptom)</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
