  <div class="phase-card appendix-card" id="appendix-colostomy">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge phase-badge-appendix">Appendix B</span>
      <h2>Colostomy Care Quick Reference Guide</h2>
    </div>

    <h3>🗺️ Types of Colostomies</h3>
    <table class="data-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Type</th><th>Location</th><th>Output Character</th><th>Clinical Notes</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>Cecostomy / Ascending</strong></td><td>Right side of abdomen</td><td>Very watery / liquid; high volume</td><td>Highest risk of dehydration and electrolyte imbalance; most challenging to manage</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Transverse</strong> (Jesus's type)</td><td>Upper abdomen (mid)</td><td>Watery to semi-formed; moderate volume</td><td>Still significant fluid losses; high education needs; daily fluid intake essential</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Descending</strong></td><td>Left side of abdomen</td><td>Semi-formed to formed</td><td>More manageable output; irrigation possible</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Sigmoid</strong></td><td>Lower left abdomen</td><td>Formed / solid</td><td>Most similar to normal stool; irrigation often possible; easiest to manage</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <div class="info-grid" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🚽 Emptying the Pouch</h3>
        <ol>
          <li>Empty when pouch is 1/3 to 1/2 full</li>
          <li>Sit on or in front of toilet</li>
          <li>Hold pouch over toilet; unclamp drain</li>
          <li>Empty contents; wipe drain end with tissue</li>
          <li>Reclamp securely</li>
          <li>Wash hands thoroughly</li>
        </ol>
        <p><em>Note: Do NOT wait until pouch is overfull — weight increases risk of seal breaking.</em></p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🔄 When to Change the Pouching System</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Every <strong>3–7 days</strong> (per manufacturer and WOC nurse guidance)</li>
          <li>Immediately if leaking, lifting, or separating from skin</li>
          <li>If peristomal skin irritation develops under the wafer</li>
          <li>Best time to change: <strong>2–4 hours after eating</strong> — stoma is less active</li>
          <li>In the morning before fluid/food intake when possible</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 style="margin-top: 0.5rem;">⚠️ Peristomal Skin Problems and Solutions</h3>
    <table class="data-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Problem</th><th>Appearance</th><th>Cause</th><th>Intervention</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Excoriation / Rash</td><td>Red, raw, weeping skin under wafer</td><td>Output leaking under barrier; irritation from output enzymes</td><td>Change pouch system; resize barrier opening; apply skin barrier powder; WOC nurse consult</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Leakage under wafer</td><td>Output visible under adhesive seal</td><td>Improper sizing; skin folds; insufficient skin prep</td><td>Re-measure stoma; use barrier paste; ensure skin completely dry before application</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Fungal rash</td><td>Bright red with satellite lesions, itching</td><td>Moist environment under wafer; especially with antibiotics</td><td>Antifungal powder under barrier; WOC nurse; keep skin dry</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Mechanical trauma</td><td>Skin stripping, bleeding from removal</td><td>Aggressive removal of adhesive barrier</td><td>Use adhesive remover; peel-push technique; warm water to loosen edges</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">🌟 Lifestyle Considerations</h3>
    <div class="compare-grid">
      <div>
        <h4>✅ Resuming Normal Activities</h4>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Diet:</strong> No permanent dietary restrictions; introduce foods gradually; 8–10 glasses water daily</li>
          <li><strong>Activity:</strong> Light activity in 4–6 weeks; avoid heavy lifting initially; most sports are possible</li>
          <li><strong>Swimming/bathing:</strong> Bathing and swimming with ostomy are safe; use waterproof tape around edges if desired</li>
          <li><strong>Travel:</strong> Carry double the supplies; keep supplies in carry-on luggage; wear pouch through security</li>
          <li><strong>Clothing:</strong> Most clothing is appropriate; high-waist clothing may be adjusted for comfort</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h4>💕 Intimacy and Sexuality</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>A colostomy does not prevent intimacy — most people resume sexual activity after healing</li>
          <li>Empty the pouch before intimate activity; use a smaller mini-pouch or ostomy cover if desired</li>
          <li>Open communication with partner reduces anxiety for both</li>
          <li>UOAA has specific resources for young adults addressing sexuality</li>
          <li>Referral to WOC nurse or counselor if concerns persist</li>
          <li>Many young adults with ostomies live full intimate lives — normalize this openly</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

