    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q2: What is a transverse colostomy and how does it differ from other types?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p>A <strong>transverse colostomy</strong> is a surgical opening created in the transverse colon (the middle portion of the large intestine, running horizontally across the upper abdomen). It may be temporary or permanent.</p>
        <table class="data-table" style="margin-top: 0.75rem;">
          <thead><tr><th>Type</th><th>Location</th><th>Output</th><th>Fluid Loss Risk</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Ascending / Cecostomy</td><td>Right lower abdomen</td><td>Liquid, high enzyme content</td><td>Very high</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Transverse (Jesus)</strong></td><td>Upper abdomen</td><td>Watery to semi-formed</td><td><strong>High</strong></td></tr>
            <tr><td>Descending</td><td>Left abdomen</td><td>Semi-formed</td><td>Moderate</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Sigmoid</td><td>Lower left abdomen</td><td>Formed / solid</td><td>Low</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p><strong>Key clinical point:</strong> The further "upstream" (toward the cecum) the colostomy is located, the more fluid and electrolytes are lost — because less colon is available to absorb water. Jesus's transverse colostomy means significant daily fluid losses that contributed directly to his dehydration admission.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q3: What are the signs of stoma ischemia or necrosis, and how do you respond?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Finding</th><th>Significance</th><th>Nursing Action</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Pink-red, moist</td><td>Normal, healthy perfusion</td><td>Document; no action required</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Pale or white</td><td>Reduced arterial flow</td><td>Notify provider promptly; assess contributing factors</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Dark red or purple</td><td>Venous congestion / ischemia</td><td><strong>NOTIFY PROVIDER</strong> — requires surgical evaluation</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Black or gray</td><td>Necrosis — tissue death</td><td><strong>EMERGENCY — notify surgeon immediately</strong></td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p><strong>Stoma ischemia</strong> most commonly occurs in the early postoperative period (within 24–48 hours) but can also develop later from pouching system pressure, hernia, or vascular compromise. Early detection through routine assessment is essential.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q4: What patient education points are essential for Jesus before discharge?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Pouch emptying technique:</strong> How to empty, when to empty (1/3–1/2 full), how to reclamp — this is the most basic and most frequent skill</li>
          <li><strong>Stoma color assessment:</strong> What normal looks like (pink-red, moist) vs. emergency signs (dark purple, black) — when to call immediately</li>
          <li><strong>Appliance change procedure:</strong> Step-by-step change with return demonstration — builds independence and prevents skin breakdown</li>
          <li><strong>Dietary and hydration guidance:</strong> 8–10 glasses water daily; foods that affect output, odor, gas; gradual food reintroduction</li>
          <li><strong>Red flag recognition:</strong> At minimum: no output &gt; 4 hours, stoma color change, fever, persistent nausea, dehydration signs</li>
          <li><strong>Resources and follow-up:</strong> WOC nurse contact, UOAA (www.ostomy.org), outpatient follow-up appointment, dietitian contact</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q5: Describe the psychosocial nursing interventions for a 28-year-old man with a new colostomy.</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Young adults with new ostomies face unique psychosocial challenges:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Body image:</strong> Validate feelings first; use therapeutic communication; never minimize the significance of the change</li>
          <li><strong>Sexuality and intimacy:</strong> Address this topic openly and professionally; assure him that intimacy is possible; provide UOAA resources specific to young adults</li>
          <li><strong>Peer support:</strong> UOAA connection to others who have successfully adapted; particularly powerful for young adults to see peers thriving</li>
          <li><strong>WOC nurse referral:</strong> Wound, Ostomy, Continence nurses are specialized in both the technical AND psychosocial aspects of ostomy adjustment</li>
          <li><strong>Involve the support person thoughtfully:</strong> Virginia is a resource, but the goal is Jesus's independence — assess his readiness and involve her with his permission</li>
          <li><strong>Gradual progression:</strong> Forcing self-care before psychological readiness increases anxiety and resistance; meet him where he is</li>
          <li><strong>Mental health referral:</strong> If body image disturbance or depression persists beyond the acute admission, formal counseling referral is appropriate</li>
          <li><strong>Motivational interviewing:</strong> "What would help you feel more in control?" — places the patient as expert on his own experience</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q6: Complete the ADPIE / Clinical Judgment Template for Jesus's primary nursing diagnosis (Deficient Fluid Volume).</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Component</th><th>Content</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Assessment (Recognition of Cues)</th><td>HR 108 bpm (tachycardia), BP 104/68 mmHg (hypotension), urine output 15 mL/hr (critically low), dark amber urine, dry/tacky mucous membranes, skin tenting &gt;2 sec, delayed cap refill 3 sec; transverse colostomy with watery output; decreased oral intake since discharge</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Nursing Diagnosis</th><td><strong>Deficient Fluid Volume</strong> r/t excessive colostomy output and decreased oral intake AEB tachycardia (HR 108), hypotension (BP 104/68), urine output 15 mL/hr, dry mucous membranes, decreased skin turgor</td></tr>
            <tr><th>SMART Goal</th><td>Patient will demonstrate adequate fluid volume AEB urine output ≥ 30 mL/hr, HR &lt; 100 bpm, and moist mucous membranes within 24 hours of initiation of IV fluid therapy</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Interventions</th><td>(1) Maintain IV 0.9% NS at 125 mL/hr per order; (2) Measure and document urine output hourly; (3) Monitor and report electrolyte results; (4) Encourage oral fluid intake as tolerated; (5) Daily weights at same time each day; (6) Assess IV site every 4 hours; (7) Monitor for fluid overload (lung sounds, edema, BP elevation); (8) Teach importance of hydration with transverse colostomy</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Rationale</th><td>0.9% NS (isotonic) expands ECF volume; hourly I&amp;O monitors response to therapy and ongoing losses; electrolytes confirm electrolyte imbalances from GI losses; oral fluids supplement IV rehydration; daily weights track fluid balance; site assessment prevents IV complications</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Evaluation</th><td>Goal met when: urine output ≥ 30 mL/hr for ≥ 2 consecutive hours; HR normalized &lt; 100 bpm; mucous membranes moist to inspection; patient reports decreased thirst; no new signs of fluid overload</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

